/span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ii) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the performance of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in relation to emissions budgets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Our conclusions drawn from these research areas are structured according to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e questions specified in the terms of the inquiry rather than by topic.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e overcome?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS does not generate electricity; it removes the CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from a fossil fuel plant, whilst at the same time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">imposing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a significant energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and financial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> penalty.  Climate change mitigation is the primary driver for CCS, and in the absence of a carb</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on market it offers no economic benefit.  For CCS to develop, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there either has to be a strong regulatory signal, or financial incentives.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS is an emerging technology, of which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">awareness and understanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; this makes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it difficult </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to predict how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it will be discussed and regarded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as full chain and commercial scale projects are deployed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  However, on provision of introductory information about CCS, initial responses do not reflect an intuitive opposition to the technology. Renewable energy supply options are typically preferred and acceptance of CCS may be conditional on it being introdu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ced as part of a portfolio of measures and not as a substitute for renewable alternatives (Shackley, McLachlan et al. 2005; O’Keefe et al, 2013). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data from focus group studies on public perceptions of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uncertainties)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trusted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; 