an><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Roberts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mander,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">201</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research conducted at Tyndall Manchester (Roberts and Mander, 2010; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O’Keefe et al, 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) suggests that from the point of view of lay publics, storage is the element of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the CCS chain which attracts the most concern.  Thus, developing appropriate regulation for the storage and monitoring of stored CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as well as ensuring that the geology of storage sites themselves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">understood</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is of paramount importance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Proximity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of local populations to the storage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> site</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly for early schemes is likely to impact on social responses to the technology. For the most part onshore storage of CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been in remote and sparsely populated areas; there has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been significant opposition where onshore storage has been attempted in more populous areas, such as Barendrecht in the Netherlands.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While there are no rules that can guarantee a development proce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eds without protest (the opportunity for opposition and debate is an essential part of the democratic process, provides learning opportunities and ultimately a check on inappropriate developments), a healthy and well run engagement process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">important in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mitigating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hostility and deliver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> genuinely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> engaged and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> positive outcome for all parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Mander and McL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">achlan 201</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation if CCS fails?</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s a central element of decarbonisation scenarios proposed by (amongst others) DECC and the IEA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(DECC, 2010; IEA  2013).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This reliance on CCS to achieve climate change mitigation targets is in spite of there, as yet, being no full scale commercial, fossil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fuel CCS plants. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is useful to consider the potential timescales for the deployment of CCS in the light of cumulative emissions.  As articulated in Anderson and Bows </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2011), the later that emissions peak before reducing, the more rapid the rate of reduct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ions have to be to remain within an emissions budget commensurate with 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C. This begs the question of whether CCS can be deployed in time, and highlights the danger of relying on CCS to the extent suggested in DECC scenarios, and points in the direction of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> demand reduction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS has also recently received some discussion in relation to the identification of unconventional gas resources in the UK and their substantial exploitation in the USA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Successive DECC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Secretaries of State</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have cited the role of CCS in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">justifying investment in shale gas production through long term compatibility with carbon budgets. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even without the development of a UK shale gas industry, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncreased production within the US could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have substantial impacts on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> energy system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Carbon bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dgets, in absolute terms, ought to be robust to these changes, however subsidiary policy, e.g. in stimulating power sector decarbonisation, also needs to be robust.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Considering CCS in the context of unconventional gas resources w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e urge caution </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> investigation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in two regards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> i) the potential for failure of delivery </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at commercial scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">internationally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ii) the performance of CCS technology in practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">points </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK’s carbon budget</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">medium to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">long term.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Neither a substantial UK shale gas industry nor significant generation from CCS powerstations is anticipated before 2030. Beyond this date, the CCC has made a credible case for the almost complete decarbonisation of electricity supply. Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t likely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not only very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">low</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> supply a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">much </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater proportion of the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to meet the UK’s international commitments around 2°C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">see Tyndall Centre’s submission to the Environmental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Audit Commission inquiry ‘Progress on Carbon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Budgets’, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Under both these circumstances, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a gas CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">life cycle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emission factor of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">~80gCO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/kWh (Hammond et al 2012) would be too high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be more than a niche </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">energy supplier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Because of the significance of leakages of methane in this estimate, the a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ctual figures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be lowered by indigenous shale gas production but raised by LNG imports. If we are to rely on CCS in delivering a large proportion of our energy supply, via </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an increasingly dominant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> grid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, then the full lifecycle ef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and uncertainties in their estimates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must be accounted for and considered in long te</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rm scenarios and strategy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the probability of exceeding 2°C wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s reduced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in line with the language of the Copenhagen Accord </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the 2012 Camp David Declar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(i.e. 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or even extended to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a more conservative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 30-40%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> chance of exceeding 2°C)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), the available global carbon would be radically reduced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (the UK government’s chosen carbon budget is premised on a 63% chance of exceeding 2°C)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Assuming the CCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s specified energy demand remains unchanged and with other things being equal, this would dramatically reduce the UK’s pre-2030 budget and essentially eliminate any emissions space post 2030. In light of this and given that the only very-low/zero carbon e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nergy supply options are renewables, some biomass sources and nuclear the relative merits of the different supply options would certainly change.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly, if the global budget remains at the level proposed by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the CCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but the apportionment of emissions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between Annex 1 and non-Annex 1 nations was to be closer to the equity framing of the Accord, with later emissions peaks for non-Annex 1 nations, the budget for the UK (and other Annex 1 nations) would again be dramatically reduced, with the relative merit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s of the very-low/zero carbon supply options changed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To put this simply, if the 2°C and equity commitments of the Copenhagen Accord and Cancun Agreements (reaffirmed at the 2012 G8 Camp David meeting) were to be adhered to, four alternative conclusions ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ise:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.43pt; padding-left:4.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A radical and sustained reduction in energy demand (probably an aggregate, across all sectors, of well over 70% within ten years)</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.43pt; padding-left:4.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A rapid and significant extension of renewable supply capacity, well beyond the level FoE consider possible in their DECC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 2050 example pathway</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 66.35pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A significant and rapid new build programme of nuclear powerstations commenced immediately and in complement with large-scale renewable supply</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.43pt; padding-left:4.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A combination of two or more of the above; one of which would need to be a reduction in ene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rgy demand (i.e. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">#</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">1) to realise the significant and immediate reductions dictated by tighter 2°C and equity constraints. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anderson, K., Bows, A., 2011. Beyond 'dangerous' climate change: emission scenarios for a new world. Philosophical Transac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions of the Royal Society a-Mathematical Physical and Engineering Sciences 369, 20-44.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC, 2010. Pathways for 2050. Department of Energy and Climate Change, London.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Hammond, Geoffrey P.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Howard, Hayley R.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Jones, Craig I.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (2013). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The energy and environm</span><span s